A Republican Strategy to Counter Obama’s Re-election
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to fight electoral fraud.
However, the Brennan Center regards the latter as a myth, claiming that electoral fraud is more rare in the United States than the number of people killed by thunderbolt.
Indeed, Republican lawyers have recorded only 300 cases of electoral fraud in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will negatively influence the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, U.S. states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
It was in this spirit that a majority of American governments enacted new laws from 2009 onwards, making the registration or voting process more difficult.
This phenomenon has gained momentum after the November 2010 elections, which included 675 new Republican representatives in 26 states.
As a result, 180 bills restricting the exercise of the right to vote in 41 states were introduced in the year of 2011.
The new electoral laws require voters to have a photo identification card and proof of US citizenship.
In addition, these laws also reduce advance voting periods, invalidate the right to register as voters on polling day and deprive citizens with judicial records of their right to vote.
Prior to the 2006 elections, no US state required voters to present a photo identification card.
Indiana was the first state to make such a demand.
The United States Supreme Court confirmed the constitutionality of Indiana law in 2008.
The Republican authorities were quick to extend the practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they had sponsored bills in 34 states to force voters to present a photo identification card.
It is important to note that, unlike in Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity card such as the health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of US citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have photo identification cards issued by a government agency in their state.
Moreover, five million new voters in 2012 did not have such an identity document.
However, it often costs more than 100 dollars to obtain the required identity card.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
Indeed, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earn less than 35,000 dollars; 18% of citizens over the age of 65, and 20% of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
Much more.
Students, voters considered to be voting more for Democratic candidates, are not allowed in several states to use their photo identification card issued by their institution.
On the other hand, the same states allow members of fishing or hunting clubs who vote more on the Republican side to use to vote the cards issued by these clubs.
Prior to 2004, no State required proof of citizenship to vote.
Arizona was the first to present such a requirement.
Since 2011, a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are US citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting Hispanic voting.
However, it appears that two out of three Hispanic voters favour the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican legislators sponsored in 2011 laws abolishing voter registration on polling day in eight states.
In addition, they have limited the right of individuals and groups to provide assistance to eligible voters.
These restrictions are not without consequences.
For example, in the 2004 general election, voter registration campaigns helped to register about 10 million citizens.
However, the measures adopted since 2009 have brought down the registration rate for new voters by 17 per cent in 2010 compared with 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators have enacted laws in five other states to reduce the advance voting period.
For example, in Florida’s 2008 general election, 33% of voters who voted in advance were African-American, while the latter accounted for only 13 percent of the state’s voters.
The same was true of the Hispanics.
They accounted for only 11% of voters, but 24% of citizens who voted in advance.
In return, whites, who made up 76 percent of voters, accounted for only 46% of voters in advance.
Of course, democratic legislators and their supporters have strongly opposed the adoption of laws restricting voter registration.
Several bills have been blocked by the vetoes of Democratic governors.
The U.S. Attorney General intervened to suspend the most controversial laws.
They were able to partially limit the damage.
For example, only 16 out of 34 States have adopted laws requiring the presentation of a photo identification card.
Nevertheless, the new rules put in place will undoubtedly make it more difficult to exercise the right to vote in 2012.
Democratic critics denounce the partisan nature of the laws that have been passed, and they see it as a clear objective of influencing the results in 2012 in key states.
A 2011 report by the Brennan Center shows that the states that have passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 votes needed by the electoral college to win the presidency.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes in the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential elections.
But one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on the participation rate.
In this sense, these measures will partly undermine the American democratic system.
