The hipped Higgs boson
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson created a whole stir-by stir-by last summer, and for good reason.
It is indeed believed that this boson participates in the mechanism responsible for the mass of everything in the Universe, just that.
And then it's the last particle whose existence is predicted by the Standard Model -- our best, or "less worse" explanation of the nature and behavior of matter -- but has not yet been observed empirically.
But for physicists, it's not yet completely safe that it's the Higgs.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we hold an authentic new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
Moreover, new data unveiled this week at a major physics congress in Kyoto seem to confirm this, but there is still a lack of data to be perfectly certain of it.
Let's assume it's the Higgs, because the chances of getting wrong seem slim, and let's see what it is.
There is, in this world, a law that is fatally inescapable that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
No way to break this rule -- and don't try too hard, you're going to hurt yourself.
Now even if particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that it also has a law of this kind: the principle of exclusion of Pauli, which states that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same "quantum state" - this "state" roughly consisting of some of their characteristics.
From there, physicists classify particles into two categories.
In one corner are good citizens named fermions, who wisely obey Pauli's principle.
And in the other the bosons are agitated, a dirty gang of anarchists who have no respect for anything -- at least not for that principle, which means that they can actually be in the same place, at the same time.
These bosons then divide into two groups, according to the site (absolutely extraordinary, by the way) The Particle Adventure, of the Berkeley Laboratories: the mesons, which we will not address here, and the "force particles", by which the great forces of nature propagate and to which the Higgs boson would be somehow related.
These bosons, we must emphasize here, are not all exotic bugs as exotic as one might think.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it's thanks to a boson of extraordinary triviality: the photon, or the "particle of light" which is the "messenger" of the electromagnetic force.
When, in fact, a particle having an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, this "disrupts" the electromagnetic field in this precise place, much like a stone thrown into a pond.
From this "disruption" arises an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing more than a photon--and therefore one of the "force-carrier" bosons.
More stable field
The same is true of the Higgs boson, except for this difference that it is another field, the Higgs field, which must be "disturbed" for this boson to appear.
Now, this Higgs field is much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, it is necessary to reach very, very high energies, a little as if it were a frozen pond from which only a very large rock could ride the surface.
That's why it takes a huge particle accelerator like CERN - the Large Hadron Collider is a 27-kilometer-circumference ring - to reach such energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is again useful for explaining the relationship between the Higgs and the mass.
It is not indeed all the particles, nor all the materials, which interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do it, but others do not - a piece of paper, for example, will never stand on a fridge on its own.
And in the same way, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do it have a mass, while others (like the photon, here) do not.
Now, what is 'can' all this research bring, asks Mrs Plamondon?
For science, this is used to verify the validity of the Standard Model (MS), and it also allows physicists to scrutinize any discrepancy between the observations and predictions of the MS.
Moreover, several of them are to be determined to find, because the slightest difference could open a door to a "new physical" and plug some of the Pattern holes.
The latter, it must be said, still has enormous shortcomings, offering no explanation for gravity (oops) or dark matter, which forms about 80% of the matter of the Universe (re-bops).
But there have been no such deviations at CERN until now.
Impact
The repercussions of this research in the daily life of Monsieur and Madame Tout-le-Monde are more difficult to predict, but it would be wrong to assume that there will be none.
Here: in the early 1960s, laser pioneers in Bell Laboratories had no suspicion of the revolution that their work would trigger.
They came up with scientific applications, but nothing else.
In fact, we already told the fire of the physicist Willard Boyle - who worked in the Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the first were pulsed), in 1962 -- the laser was initially seen as a "lab gangget".
Imagine...
And then, the applications can also come from all the instrumentation that surrounds the search.
For example, the same Willard Boyle developed a small light sensor in 1969 during his work in optics.
This sensor, although it was not his original intention at all, now serves as an "eye" for all the digital cameras in the world, and earned him the Nobel Prize in Physics 2009.
This, of course, does not mean that the activities of the LHC will necessarily transform our lives, but it means that, really, we never know...
