With Bitcoin, all the nodes of the network are bankers of the books of accounts, auditors, currency issuers, and buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users is in fact made between two e-mail addresses in the manner of an e-mail.
Except that a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically by a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the content of the file, it is also possible to ensure that the bitcoins exchanged do exist in the public account book, distributed throughout the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction in this book.
It requires the resolution of a mathematical challenge to computers, and the winner of which, as a kind of temporary central banker, will have the privilege of adding this extra line.
This is a file hash phase, i.e. transforming a large file into a shorter and single digital fingerprint.
The computers "take" the new transaction and add a number before "chopping" the whole.
The aim is to find the number which gives a particular imprint (many of zeros at the beginning).
Once this number has been found, the other nodes easily verify that it is the right one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of all the other transactions; any change would change the fingerprint.
If, to defraud, one user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other remaining orphaned because the two have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the challenge won 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided by two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to the hundred millionth, which leaves room for ...
The difficulty of the challenge is also met at each increase in the computing power.
The life of the network has already had ups and downs.
Websites providing services for Bitcoin were attacked and the bitcoins in stolen repositories.
"The flaw used is not about the protocol itself," says Pierre Noizat, who has just launched Paymium, a real-currency payment company using the Bitcoin network.
