In Israel, holy places, the centre of the world and a sea of brine await Ukrainian tourists
The Promised Land combines greatness of biblical truths, modern comfort and wilderness.
Argoumenty i Fakty has chosen five main reasons for travelling to Israel.
Go and worship the holy places
A must-see rendezvous: the shores of the Jordan River, where Jesus was baptized.
It is said that whoever penetrates these "baptismal funds" will be touched by divine grace.
As for Galilee, it is the land of the miracles of Jesus: where water was changed into wine, where Jesus walked on the water, where he appeased the storm or where fishing was miraculous.
It was in this very place that Jesus appeared before his disciples after the Resurrection.
But where you will find the most holy places, it is in Jerusalem.
Believers travel through the Street of Suffering or the Way of the Cross (Latin: the Via Dolorosa).
This path begins near the fortress Antonia (the courtroom), where the trial was held, then led by the streets of the old city to the Church of the Holy Sepulchre on the Golgotha, to the place of the Crucifixion, then to that of the Stone of the Anointing and the Burial.
It is here that the Christian centre of the world is located, a symbol of the salvation of humanity.
According to Christian legend, the monastery of the Cross is erected at the place where the tree used to make the cross on which Jesus was crucified.
Jerusalem is also home to the most sacred place of the Jews: the Western Wall which constitutes the rest of a temple destroyed by the Romans in 70 BC. D-C.
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave small words with prayers that are then answered.
Travel in height
Visit the ruins of the Fortress of the Fortress, a former refuge against enemies built by Herod the Great in 25 BC. D-C. for his family.
These ruins lie on the steep rocks of a mountain 450 m above sea level.
Only mountaineering enthusiasts can go there by their own means.
For the others, a cable car takes them to this top full of history.
In the north of the country, between 1,600 and 2,040 m above sea level, is the ski resort of Mont Hermont, which hosts many tourists in winter.
A shuttle bus can take you from the foot of the mountain.
The ski slopes are 45 km long.
Old beliefs want pagan gods to have once inhabited the top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
This country is home to nearly 300 museums.
It is impossible to visit them all during a single stay.
Here are the five most interesting ones that are really worth the detour.
First of all, the Israel Museum located near the Knesset (parliament).
It houses the ancient manuscripts of Qumran, or Dead Sea manuscripts, discovered in the caves of the Desert of Judea, as well as nearly 500 miles of archaeological and anthropological objects.
See also: Tel Aviv Museum of Art.
It mainly exhibits the paintings of Impressionists and Expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall and Picasso.
In Acre, Hammam Al-Basha awaits you with its Turkish baths consisting of castings of visitors and overseers of the time.
Once in Caesarea, enter the only private Ralli Museum where you can admire sculptures by Rodin.
There are no guides or souvenir shops.
Entry is free and donations are prohibited.
The fifth museum is the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem Memorial, located in Tel Aviv, which returns to the most dramatic historical pages in history.
The most tragic part is the children's memorial, built in memory of the 1.5 million children exterminated in the concentration camps and gas chambers.
You enter it and enter into total darkness.
Stars glitter.
You then hear the names of Jewish children and the names of countries in which they died.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Health and well-being
The three major seaside resorts of Israel are located on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea, the Red Sea and the Dead Sea.
Each of them offers swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and giant aquariums.
Note: you can bathe in the Red Sea even in winter, because the water temperature does not drop below 21 degrees while the air temperature can reach 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer and you can swim all year round.
By the way, it is the most unique sea in the world: it occupies the lowest point on Earth, 417 m below sea level.
The azure-colored water contains brine and very easily retains bathers, even those who cannot swim.
The surrounding landscapes are surreal beauty.
We come there to carry out a treatment based on salt water, silt, curative sludge and to treat various diseases such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes but also to relax.
Discover the secrets of antiquity
They are guarded by the old town of Tel Aviv, Jaffa, on the shores of the Mediterranean Sea.
It is crossed by the famous Via Maris, which connects Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia.
The city is mentioned in the Greek and Egyptian legends of antiquity.
According to legend, it was here that Noah built his arch and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom he lived a long and happy life here.
Tourists particularly like to walk in the narrow alleys that bear the names of the zodiac's signs.
It is said that if you touch the street walls corresponding to "your" sign, fate will smile at you.
In Jaffa you can see newlyweds coming to take photo shoots of everything from Israel and even other countries.
In Caesarea, city of King Herod, you can stroll through the Roman theatre, "conquer" the Fortress of the Crusaders.
Under the Roman Empire, Caesarea was the main city of Judea and the residence of Roman prosecutors, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theater is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Note to tourists
If you're going to Israel, don't worry about your English: about 30% of the population speaks Russian.
For your trip, it is better to prefer dollars to the euro, because they are easily tradable in shekels (today 1 dollar is equivalent to 3.8 shekels).
In the case of urban transport, it is mainly buses, but Jerusalem is equipped with a fast tram and Haifa has the only subway line in the country, consisting of six stations and capable of connecting the lower and upper parts of the city.
It is almost an underground funicular.
Travelling in all types of public transport costs 6 shekels and allows you to make changes for 1 hour 30 minutes.
In Israel, Jewish tradition is intended to celebrate the Sabbath on Saturdays.
From Friday evening to sunset on Saturdays, markets, shops and public transport stop their activity.
And the work week starts on Sunday morning.
Many cafes, restaurants and hotels serve only kosher food, which excludes pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes made of both milk and meat.
It offers a multitude of lamb and beef dishes, soups and desserts based on coconut milk but also hummus, traditional Jewish paste, various sauces, moulded chickpea balls, falafels, fruits and vegetables.
