Last week, at the meeting of Ministers of the European Space Agency countries, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of the European Space Agency, and is the second member State of the former Eastern Bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had started working closely with ESA in 1994 and in the years that followed participated in a number of the Agency's projects.
However, the road from Poland to space began much earlier.
Even before the Second World War, passionate Poles were working on space flights; they did not always have understanding.
I would like to refer, for example, to the A conference. At the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933, during which he presented ideas from his avant-garde book entitled "Introduction to astronauts".
The development of this young engineer (born 1905) left the cold listeners, and years later Oternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, in France, the Robert Esnault-Pelterie Prize and André Louis Hirsch won the prize "Introduction to astronautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899–1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and astronautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books on this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a world-renowned astronautic propagator, his contribution was notably rewarded by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters on the far side of the Moon.
As early as 1925, a raisin was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
It is also not clear whether the rocket should be used to propel or brake the raisin.
The only known information on this draisine was that of the press of the time.
From 1933, Polish artillery began to devote themselves to rockets.
The research was carried out by the Institute of Technology, Uzbrojenia, in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustaw Mokrzyckiego.
The documents kept show that this research had reached the stage of testing.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the searches stopped.
In 1937, the plans of a photoelectric hunting rocket, drawn by the engineer Rohoizski, appeared in the specialized press and the following year the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki was published.
Both projects were intended to use rocket engines as a military.
Just before the war, all plans for the use of rocket technology were carried out by the provisional scientific advisory committee ("Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all work.
This committee had been established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the beginning of the war ended its activities.
After the war, further work on aeronautics was published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish astronautic society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, reference is made to a company in the November 1954 issue of the newspaper Problem, which contains four more detailed articles on aeronautics.
In one of these articles, written by Professor M. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create a society dedicated to astronautics
By that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that the field of space research had a future.
In early 1956, the Polish Astronautic Society (PTA) made efforts to join the international astronautic federation (established in 1951) and by the autumn PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first president of the PTA, Kazimierz zarankiewicz (1902–1959), became vice-president of the international astronautics federation.
He retained his office until his death in 1959.
Beginning in 1956, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM meteorologiczna (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) weather rocket, which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 meters had a length of 80 cm and weighed a little less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version was built, RM-1A, and in the summer of 1959, flight tests for the RM-2 two-stage rocket were initiated in the Bledov Desert.
The rocket had a length of 1.4 metres and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The next prototype should have been able to perform concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have had a range of up to 14.5 km and used to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was halted.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962-1965, was succeeded by the first RM rockets.
This rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of the space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space with a volume of 0.4 liters, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 liters and in Meteor-1C 0.62 litre.
The maximum range of all these types of equipment was 37 km.
In the period 1965-1968, the Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aeronautical institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg at an altitude of about 60 km.
Subsequently, the Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were built.
Mention should also be made of the entry of Poland into the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of a COSPAR national committee two years later.
Under the Interkosmos programme, Poland also participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites and, in 1978, pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second non-Sovitic cosmonaut in this programme after Vladimur Remek.
