The movie Argo: When it's all wrong, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a crowd of protesters of Islamist students stormed the American embassy in Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostage.
They were to be released in exchange for the Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, which had been supporting his regime for several decades.
The situation did not offer the US administration a positive outcome; it could not, indeed, abandon the Shah, because it would have seriously shaken the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to secure the release of the hostages.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, a blow even later aggravated by the fiasco of the attempt to release hostages by force.
The sequestered diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate aroused a wave of solidarity and an anti-Iranian sentiment in the United States.
The Iranian debacle strongly contributed to the defeat of Jimmy Carter against Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The film Argo, by actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offered America a small victory.
Just before she was busy, six employees escaped from the embassy.
After complicated adventures, they found themselves in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran with a shocking cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a film crew who came to spotted for the shooting of a great science fiction film.
Combination of genders
The exfiltration expert's plan, Tony Mendez, required Hollywood's collaboration.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized magazines reported on the film project, press conferences were organized and a fictional production company had real offices.
The details of the operation remained secret for a long time, the film being based on Tony Mendez's memories.
The Affleck film is an unusual combination of several genres.
It is on the one hand a realistically designed political thriller but also a "caper movie", a successful narrative, a treachery - such as, for example, in the Ocean's 11, twelve and thirteen trilogy.
The atmospheres follow one another: sequences of Tehran in the documentary style (in the subtitled sequences are presented with iconic photographs from the time of the events and the way in which, thanks to these photos, these same situations have been transcribed in the film, there are no major differences),
lighter passages from Hollywood, treated with irony and a little exaggeration,
and then scenes from CIA headquarters and other institutions with costume men discussing the situation around conference tables, in the corridors and on the phone...
Ben Affleck managed to restart his career in a remarkable way.
From a ridiculous actor, he became a respected director and his acting ceased to arouse ironic remarks.
Argo was his third feature film after the dark policeman "Gone Baby Gone" (2007) and the thriller "The town" (2010).
It is also Affleck's first film that is not taking place in his hometown, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the features that placed its first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of the atmosphere in Argo where the role of Tehran is "held" by Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place in the streets, during the reconstruction of real facts; the initial sequence of the embassy's fall is impressive by its clarity which also suggests confusion and unpredictability occurring when suddenly, in a given place, a page of history is written.
Affleck and his collaborators achieved a similar effect in the fictional scenes (the fake filming team in the Tehran Bazaar).
Too many actions in too many places
The director had to settle for a subject that actually offers few thrilling scenes, in the cinematic sense of the word.
He's doing very well, he sometimes adds some elements to reality, and there, the result isn't always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is sidelined by a phone call in America and the pursuit of the airstrip is quite pulled by the hair).
Argo's weakness lies in his dissipated character, due to the need to show too many events to too many different places.
While it is true that Alan Arkin and John Goodman are quite charming in their role as Hollywood cooperators, their characters would have deserved a greater place and they are not, far from it, the only ones in this case.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of dramatic tension, and is seen with moderate interest, enjoying the realization and retro style of the 1970s.
It trains the spectator, but with difficulty.
As a reminder of a story still, in a way, unfinished to this day, and as an illustration of the exaggerated nature of the representation of the secret services as omnipotent and omniscient, he does the trick.
