Spijkenisse, a dormitory town that is not attractive to the gates of Rotterdam, holds a rather particular record.
The municipality of 80,000 has the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to restore some neurons to the brains, the city decided a few years ago to contribute to the general culture and to reproduce the seven fictitious bridges that appear on the euro banknotes in the form of beautiful little miniatures made of painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
For example, the city authorities realized that there was only one way to get back on statistics: the construction of a library.
Winy Maas, from the Rotterdam architects MVRDV, master of bold stick diagrams and creator of mind-of-headed and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with its usual phlegm and ran for the competition in 2003 with five books under the arm and a sneer on the face.
And as the members of the jury looked at each other again, bewildered and shrugged their shoulders, Maas, hoars him, stacked his books of choice in order of size to make a pyramid, and ended his speech backed by activist arguments by a: "common dear."
There it is, my proposal for the mountain of books by Spijkenisse, or as they say, the Boekenberg.
Nine years later, the 30 million mountain sprang from land.
The building is part of a revitalization project, which also includes an underground car park, a supermarket, a post office and a few buildings and adjoining houses for a total of 50 dwellings.
In early November, the book mountain received the second "Best Library of NL 2012" award.
In addition, the project was selected for the 2012 Dutch National Wood Award.
Thus, this little dull village, which until today had nothing more to offer than a postmodern pedestrian area and a mayor's office of a mind-boggling ugly city, whose white facades invite to think that they house a dairy, has been enriched by a contemporary architectural work.
The most important thing is that Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in its history.
The long way to reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under cheese bell.
Admittedly, an elevator transports you to the heart of the massif, but the real joys of reading and architecture open up to you when you tread the floor of the building to discover its topography.
The extirpated glass interior is bright and clear, the Dutch brick floor and elegant street lights speak unequivocally speak the language of municipal public squares.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We are already looking at public benches, dogs and little boys and girls playing with balls.
And books, books and books everywhere.
'Normally, the library rays are along the facade and in the middle is a large and dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal,' explains Willy Maas.
We completely upset the classic spatial configuration and opened the playback spaces from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the book mountain has been skilfully furnished: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the environmental centre and the building's technical centre.
A particular beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes panelling, sometimes balustrades, sometimes staircase ramps.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even hardened architects and building engineers do not want unknown materials.
'We wanted to work with recycled materials,' explains Joop Trouborst, project leader of the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
For example, one day we found an ad hoc waste from agriculture in a Frisian agricultural company.
In the Netherlands, a one-millimetre-thick synthetic membrane has been used for years as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and we're saving time.
The thin membrane is used for one or two seasons, then it can be discarded.
For the library, the membrane was compressed, for the first time in such quantities, into plates with a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the influence of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and turns into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, the smell of which evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
After almost 500 metres, the literary café offers us a stunning view of the city, but also of Dutch croquettes and ficus in pots.
