The temperature of the building is regulated by geothermal energy.
Although the mountain of books is below a bell of glass, the sun only lights the interior for a short time, even on fine days.
The thick wooden beams crossed with respect to the glass facade serve as sun visors, intercepting a large part of the rays.
The ambient atmosphere is very pleasant.
Fully automated blinds take care of the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the above-mentioned septic computer scientist, has already ventured into the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was also already there.
Cynthia Bogarde, a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes the Boekenberg as "the soul finally found" of Spijkenisse.
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, every citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure made it possible to fill the gaps of the library which was not yet completely furnished (today it has 70,000 pounds).
The concept is a success.
The rays are overflowing from all directions.
For architect Winy Maas, "there's nothing worse than a half-empty library."
"I believe that our invitation has created a certain relationship between every citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's only for decoration."
Thus, MVRDV has reached the main discipline that is called, in professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse wrote a new page of literary history.
Even though she may look young and undied.
Finally, it is a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a bigger role."
Germany chose abstention in the vote on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on US-EU relations, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany announced its intention to vote against the Palestinian demand for observer state status at the United Nations.
But then she chose abstention.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not agree with what the Israelis have done in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious, as it has special relations with Israel.
But I also think it does not support the American position either.
Germany wanted to assert its independence, but it was not too critical of Israel.
During the insurgency in Libya in March 2011, Germany also chose abstention in the vote on the establishment of a no-fly zone.
In the end, NATO imposed this measure.
Is Germany having difficulty in taking a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason for this is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from an American-defined policy and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of a coherent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans therefore clashed with several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still groping to find this role, but they are on the road to a 'more normal' foreign policy.
An external policy, as in France or Great Britain
What does the term 'normal' foreign policy mean for the Germans in practice?
It shows the willingness to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national issues.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, and therefore by exports and its relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
German economic interests are, to some extent, different from those of the other major powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position on the conflict in the Middle East and abstention from the UN vote?
First of all, Germany has important opportunities in the Middle East, especially in the Gulf countries.
That is why Berlin must be careful not to offend public opinion, but also the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a determining factor.
However, I would not give too much importance to this, because this is not an exclusively unilateral relationship.
But this is in any case a decisive element in German strategic reflections.
Is Germany harming its relations with the United States by choosing abstention in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I believe that Europeans and Americans fully understand the German position.
That is why I believe that the fracture is not as serious as it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will be more respected.
Indeed, Germany has thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, there are diverse views on the Palestinian initiative.
On the other hand, the United States has announced its veto with a clear voice.
Do opinions differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the American domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama administration is secretly showing a great understanding of the European position.
But given the political configuration of the country, the government cannot, of course, defend its position publicly.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not as great as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is far from overwhelmed with enthusiasm for Netanyahu’s policy.
Is Germany having difficulties in reconciling its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners, on the other?
I think it doesn't make things any easier for the Germans.
Obviously, it would be a little simpler for the Germans if there were a coherent and uniform European policy, but today it is not.
They cannot therefore be part of a broader political line and must affirm their unique position.
This is what they are doing now in the question of the euro.
In my opinion, Germany will assume a leading role in the future and will push Europe to adopt a European position.
It is not easy for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This issue has always been a delicate issue.
But in my view, the Germans are well aware that they must play a more independent role.
Is Germany being a major player on the international stage, does Germany want to take on a key role?
Or does it still find it difficult to assume leading roles?
Germany is still not used to it, and this is always uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country still has difficulty playing a more important role.
If we look, for example, at the euro crisis, we notice that every time Germany decides to weigh more, there are many anti-German sentiments that are heard.
It doesn't make things any easier for the Germans.
In fact, it is always the same problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
It has to deal with a wide range of neighbours and opinions, and that is not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European policy is only diminishing, but at the moment the EU is not filling this gap, so who is it still?
The Germans will simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant to them and if they're all less appreciated, it's life.
Stephen Szabo is the deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute in which academics and policy experts from Europe and North America together analyse the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, US foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
