Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most common sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydies and gonorrhoea (or gonorrhoea).
Common STIs are HIV, human papilloma virus, genital herpes or hepatitis.
The pubic lice and scabies belong to parasitic ISTs.
Which groups are mainly concerned?
Syphilis and gonorrhoea often appear in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute estimates that sexual contact between men is responsible for at least four out of five cases of syphilis reported in Germany.
In heterosexual adults, chlamydie-related infections, trichomoniasis, candidiasis (fungal), gonorrhoea and human papilloma virus are common sexually transmitted diseases.
The rate of HIV spread among heterosexual adults is relatively low in Germany. However, some 20% of new HIV infections are observed within this group.
In young people, there is a significantly higher rate of chlamyd infections than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections are for young people aged 15 to 25.
In addition, human papilloma virus in Germany is common among young people.
How many infections affect?
It is not compulsory to report all sexually transmitted diseases.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of cases of syphilis has more than doubled in 10 years: the figure has risen from 1,967 in 2001 to 3.698 in 2011.
Since 2007, the number of new HIV infections has been decreasing.
In 2011, there were about 2,700 cases.
This represents a decrease of one tenth compared to the previous year.
What are the symptoms of a sexual illness?
Infectious diseases can cause abscesses in the genitals, urinary pain, white discharge, pain in the lower abdomen and the appearance of spots and warts.
However, they do not regularly cause any pain or other symptoms and therefore remain hidden.
How can we protect ourselves?
Condoms may reduce the risk of infection, but they do not protect to 100 per cent.
This is because pathogens of sexually transmitted diseases can also be transmitted through lubricant infection or close body contact.
Experts therefore recommend that any person who often changes sexual partners regularly undergo regular examinations.
Most rapidly detected STIs can be cured and late sequelae can be avoided.
