The Norwegian rakfisk: is it the most fragrant fish in the world?
The five million people in Norway benefit from one of the highest standards of living, not only in Europe, but also in the world.
Could the secret of the country's success be linked to the locals' appetite for an extremely fragrant fish?
Take advanced cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a pile of wet and dirty soccer clothes.
Wait a week.
And you get the disturbing smell of the rakfisk, one of the most popular dishes in Norway.
I'm in the small town of Fagernes, about 3 hours from Oslo.
It's snowing, the landscape is spectacular -- and this smell, omnipresent, pervades the air.
The rakfisk consists of trout sprinkled with salt and fermented in water for a period of time - depending on the smell you want it to exhale - which can be up to a year old.
When the darkness sets in and it is cold, the Norwegians gather en masse to attend a festival that takes place here in Fagernes, dedicated to this incredible culinary speciality.
"You eat raw, then you swallow a glass of aquavit," explains Havard Halvarsen, a full-time local firefighter who is also known as 'Rakfisk General', responsible for managing the festival.
Around us, people swallow small pieces of fish and put on a large amount of beverage.
'Some people prefer aquavit to rakfisk,' adds Havard.
The drink kills the smell.
I'm trying a few pieces.
If you can avoid passing it under your nose, it's not bad - it's reminiscent of sushi that would have spent long hours on a bus.
The rakfisk dates back to a time when Norway was poor, before the invention of refrigeration, fish was immersed in air-tight water barrels and then salted in autumn.
Then, during the winter, once fermented well, the fish came out and - no doubt with the senses diminished by alcohol - eaten.
In the previous generation, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country to find work, emigrating mainly to the United States.
Now the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants, attracted by full employment, high wages and a comprehensive health system.
The Swedes, their old rivals whose country was not so richer until long ago, cross the border to come to work.
The rakfisk is considered to be something important, a vital, albeit scenting, part of Norway's past.
This is one of the most expensive dishes.
But everything is expensive - a small pint of beer or a sandwich will cost you 10 dollars each.
Norway does not often make a fuss about it in international news, which is not to be displeased.
Here, people are not willing to talk about Anders Breivik, the right-wing extremist racist who shot and killed 77 people, including women and children.
When they refer to this killing, they talk about the "migration of 22 July".
Norwegians find it difficult to accept that in their peaceful country one of them could have committed such an act of barbarity.
Since the early 1970s, Norway owes its wealth to its oil and gas industry, one of the largest in the world.
'But oil is not the only reason why we succeed,' explains Anna, our waitress, with a blonde hair and in the eyes of a piercing blue, the image of Nordic welfare, with a rakfisk tray in her hand.
We are - how do you say - prudent people.
His English, like that of most people who live here, is perfect.
We're discreet, we don't like to get noticed.
Norway has managed its oil wealth with great caution - everything except a small percentage of oil from this industry is invested in a special fund for future generations.
When other countries were throwing money out of the window, in the years that led us to the international financial crisis, Norway has been able to keep its purse strings tight.
'As long as you can ski in winter and go hiking in the summer, we are happy,' says Anna.
'Without forgetting the rakfisk,' she adds in a carefree laugh.
I stand in the snow and line up to buy food - I got my dose of rakfisk.
On the menu, a hamburger composed of momentum, a real discovery, it's excellent.
But tonight, the smell of fish is everywhere.
The hotel I'm staying in is one of the many places where rakfisk is served for dinner and where you can vote for the best of them -- or perhaps for the most odorant of them.
There's a TV show where the presenter wears a butterfly knot, surrounded by rakfisk plates.
It feels like the Eurovision contest.
"What score did you give to the best fish in the Thor-Juergen mountains?"
"Here's our dots, Havard."
We hear laughter and applause.
A man falls from his chair, perhaps because of the abuse of aquavit.
Or maybe it's because of the smoke emanating.
The Mexican Enrique Pena Nieto is making a difficult start.
As incoming President Enrique Pena Nieto prepares to take up his duties in Mexico, Will Grant of the BBC is interested in the challenges ahead and the many expectations of the people.
Road traffic in Mexico City is particularly bad at the moment.
In a city where congestion is normally legion, a safety barrage has been set up since Monday, blocking several key road accesses in the capital and causing real chaos on the roads.
However, the aim was not to prevent people from going to work, but to prevent demonstrators from reaching Parliament.
Next Saturday, Mexico’s new president, Enrique Pena Nieto, will receive the presidential scarf to become the nation’s new president.
