"I hope he will be as good as president as he was when he was governor," Congressman Olvera told Valle del Bravo.
However, this is exactly what the families of the victims of Ciudad Neza fear most.
Bradley Manning did not complain of ill-treatment, prosecutors say.
Prosecutors are trying to counter the claims of abuse that Bradley Manning was allegedly subjected during his detention.
The trial concerns Manning's detention in a military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defence wants to close the case on the grounds that Manning's kidnapping was carried out under extremely difficult conditions.
The soldier is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents.
The prosecutors tried to demonstrate on Friday that Private Bradley Manning -- accused of causing the greatest leak of confidential information in the history of the U.S. Army -- missed many opportunities to complain about the ill-treatment he claimed to have been subjected in his military detention.
During cross-examination with Manning, during a preliminary hearing in Ft. Meade, Maryland, Prosecutor Maj. Ashden Fein claimed that records of weekly visits to Manning by officers during his nine months of detention in Quantico, Virginia, revealed no complaints about his treatment.
Cross-examination -- during a hearing, the defence filed a motion requiring the Manning case to be closed on the grounds that the kidnapping was in very difficult conditions and constituted a sufficiently severe punishment -- occurred a day after Manning testified to his desire to commit suicide during his detention.
The military intelligence analyst, who was arrested in June 2010, is accused of stealing thousands of confidential documents during his service in Iraq.
The documents were then published online by WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks never confirmed that Manning had been their source.
At Friday's hearing, Fein discussed with Manning the forms that the officers had completed after their meeting with Manning during his detention in Quantico military prison, where he was subjected to maximum prison isolation from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers posed questions to Manning and recorded his answers.
When Fein referred to the forms on Friday, Manning acknowledged that his custody's treatment was "excellent" and that the treatment he had had in the prison was generally "very professional."
The forms do not file any complaints of ill-treatment, although the officers have directly questioned him about his prison treatment, Fein said.
Manning replied that he had expressed oral concerns about certain problems and that the visiting officers had discussed his concerns and indicated that they would deal with them, but they did not record the problems raised.
"They wrote 'no problem' (after addressing the concerns), and however, this did not mean that I hadn't raised any problems,' said Manning.
Military Judge Col. Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not complained about his treatment in a January 2011 interview with the special committee that had met to discuss the suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning replied that his intention during the meeting was to change his restrictive status indicating a "risk of injury".
The military stated that they had assigned it this restrictive status -- a level below close surveillance for the risk of suicide -- for its protection and the safety of others.
"I wanted the staff to know that I was doing well, and I wanted to have this status removed from me... in order to get a better quality of life from my point of view," said Manning.
Manning testified on Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and his transfer to Kuwait, where he was detained for nearly two months before being transferred to the Marine Corps base military prison in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He stated that he had considered committing suicide while in Kuwait and fainting once because of the heat.
He added that the fact that the failure to have been kept informed of what was going to happen to him or what was happening in the rest of the world was very distressing.
"My world was reduced to Camp Arafjon, to this cage," Manning said on Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
Once on Quantico, Manning said that he had spent most of his time in a small cell -- at least 9 p.m. and sometimes over 23 hours -- without a company.
Manning also added that the only items available to him were a mattress, a blanket, tongs, clothes and his glasses.
He tried to stay on the move, because sleeping or lying down during the day was contrary to the rules.
Manning also clarified that when he tried to sleep, he had a light in his eyes, lit outside his cell.
If the guards did not see his face when he turned around at night, they would wake him up so that they could see his face.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal complaint about the treatment suffered by Manning in January 2011.
Manning was placed in a military prison in Fort Leavenworth, Kansas, in April 2011.
Also on Friday, the judge asked Manning about an allegation reported in his testimony on Thursday -- that after being forced to sleep naked overnight in his cell in Quantico, he was forced to stand naked in front of the guards and other inmates one morning during the appeal.
Manning testified that at no time was he allowed to cover himself with cover during the call.
During the judge's questions on Friday, Manning stated that he had deduced from his guard order that he had to drop his cover that might have concealed his nakedness, but admitted that no one had ordered him to release it.
Manning testified on Thursday that he had been forced to sleep naked the night before, as he would have tried to prove to an officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning reportedly told the officer that he could have used the elastic band of his underpants or flip-flops to hurt himself, but that he had not.
That night, Manning testified that his underwear, flip-flops, and glasses had been removed from his cell.
His lawyers hope that at least the judge will take into account his experiences during his detention and that he will significantly reduce his sentence if he were to be convicted before a court martial, a trial that is expected to be held early next year.
The defence stated that Manning is considering pleading guilty to the least serious offences and fighting for the abandonment of other charges deemed too extreme.
The hearing is scheduled to resume this weekend, with prosecutors who should argue that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon confirmed that Manning was incarcerated in accordance with the regulations governing the conditions of detention of all detainees in Quantico.
The charges against Manning include theft of public property or documents, collusion with the enemy, resulting in the illegal publication of information on the Internet, and the transmission of national defence information.
If all counts are charged, he is liable to life imprisonment.
