Laws for neutral cigarette packets have come into force in Australia
Warnings and photos of sick organs cover dark green packets that are all the same, regardless of brand
This law that came into force in Australia is a world first, logos and colours have been replaced by dark olive green and horrendous photos of sick organs and depictions of children and babies whose illnesses were caused by their parents's smoking.
Apart from the different photos and health warnings, the only difference between packets, since this Saturday, is the name of the brand, printed in small print on all packets.
This is the strictest tobacco packaging regime in the world.
The Australian federal government has stated that the aim is to deter young people from smoking by suppressing any glamorous representation.
Studies have shown that if people have not started smoking before the age of 26, there's a 99% chance they're never starting.
'Even when they are very young, children understand the message conveyed by tobacco manufacturers through their brand image,' said Federal Minister of Health Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that revealed, for example, that children associated the crown with a logo to a princess.'
Although Australia has the lowest smoking rate in the world and these changes have little impact on the benefits of multinationals, other countries are considering a similar approach.
The tobacco industry has lobbied the law.
