The world's toughest profession: the human mules of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, Indonesian volcano wearers risk their lives and health by carrying 70 kilograms of sulphur through the steep stone trails.
There are people for whom work is a hell and others who literally work in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their living by carrying the sulphur of the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
It must work daily to the bottom of the crater, where the sulphur dioxide from the bowels of the earth solidifies in contact with the air.
After harvesting large sulfur rocks, which weigh nearly 70 kilograms, he installs them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through the steep paths.
There is only 250 meters up to the top of the volcano that rises to 2.386 meters above sea level, but the exhausted porters take more than 40 minutes to climb this distance, at a turtle-like appearance, keeping the balance and measuring their steps so as not to stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a misstep could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who made a fatal fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 euro cents for each kilogram of sulphur extracted.
Once up, they make their way between the tourists who photograph them as if they were circus beasts, and painfully carrying heavy baskets, they walk the 3 kilometers to the balance that a mining company has set up a little below at 1.850 meters.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, it can be said, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (euro cents) per kilo of sulphur.
It then sells it to the petrochemical industry of 10,000 (83 euro cents) since this ore is very present in everyday life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even bleach sugar.
'As we transport about 70 kilos, we earn about Rs. 46,000 (3.8 euros) for each trip,' explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
Each takes 3 hours and he finishes exhausted, but this allows him to earn 138,000 rupees (11.50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems to be a misery for such a superhuman effort, it is three times what it would gain in the fields.
"The income of the miners is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid for 15,000 rupees (EUR 1.220) per day and where the average monthly wage is 2 million rupees (EUR 167)", says the carrier who used to work as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was Rs. 75,000 (Euro6.20) a day and the job was not as difficult, but Anto came back near his family to Banyuwangi, a village close to the volcano, for a reason that in Indonesia is as indisputable as the sulphur: 'I married a young girl from Bali, where they are Hindu, and I brought her back to Java to Java.'
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, cough constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At 27, he spent three of his life defying the danger on the Kawah ljen, but the sulphur has already begun to charge him for the bill even though he covers his face with a mask and wears special gloves.
Anto suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, cough constantly and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases released by the volcano.
