I won't retire, I'll die here because the volcano is my whole life.
Although sulfur damages the throat and irritates the eyes when the wind turns and traps the miners in the thick columns of smoke that come out of the volcano, they are so hardened that no one complains of suffering from serious diseases... to which are obviously added their usual respiratory problems, artthrosses, pain in the knees and shoulders, deformed by the weight of the baskets.
By balancing the basket on his back, Unainik, aged 53, can only charge 50 kilograms.
Every day, he and his companions extract 15 tons of sulphur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to the Tamansari warehouse, 18 kilometers away by a weed-infested goat trail.
"I won't retire, I'll die here because the volcano is my whole life," says Unainik, opening his mouth well, unveiling several missing teeth.
The eldest of his five children, aged 30, also works as a sulphur carrier.
Time passes, but misery perpetuates from generation to generation one of the most difficult occupations in the world: that made by the human mules of the Kawah ljen volcano.
Singapore seeks babies to save the economy
Singaporeans blame the lack of children for career, stress and the cost of home ownership.
"The people of Singapore must develop".
I'm a husband and a patriot, you're my wife and a patriot, let's do our civic duty and give life.
It may seem implausible that these words come from an advertisement for mint pellets, but despite that, or perhaps because of that, the video spread like wildfire on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
The lyrics come from a rap group that uses local references like "Let's put a polchinelle in the drawer" to make fun of Singapore's birth rate.
BBH, the advertising agency behind the video, hopes to draw attention to the problem in a fun way through this advertisement.
Its creative director, Douglas Hamilton, said he wanted to use the power of music to make people fulfil "their national duty".
It's only for the Internet, so we were able to make it fun and fun.
This is the main problem in that country.
We are the worst in the world in the area of birth rates, so we felt that this was something we had to address.
We knew that the government had tried several things like throwing pheromone fragrances or organizing speed-dating nights.
Many of these ideas were creative, but they didn't necessarily work.
So we thought the following: What's more creative to solve this problem than to make it a rap song?
1.2 children
Singapore's government does not take it as much lightly.
It spends USD 1,300 a year on policies to encourage its citizens to have more children.
A government measure in favour of marriages and fathers grants up to 15,000 dollars per child, extends maternity leave and distributes tax benefits.
But all of this has had little effect.
Singapore is a rich, high-tech city-state of Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leaders and its strict social controls.
Singapore's birth rate, in accordance with its national distribution of population, currently stands at 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was above 2, considered the turnover rate, was in 1976.
Why do Singaporeans not have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, Director of Marriage and Family Policies of the National Population Division, said it was due to "better education" and "a wider choice of career opportunities".
