The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why the party in Singapore last year experienced its worst election results since independence.
Since the elections, they have tried to correct the problem with the introduction of higher quotas and taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While the fall in the birth rate has known effects on a country's economic growth, tax revenues, health costs and immigration policies, Singapore's example also has unintended consequences.
The government tried to avoid the construction of many small houses.
For example, it started to reach the real estate sector.
Urban development authorities have begun to control the number of small apartments, known as the "shoebox", which can be built in specific areas of the city.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and are very successful in selling.
However, the authorities were concerned that they could promote a single lifestyle and discourage developers wishing to build large family houses.
But Lim Yew Soon, managing director of the real estate company EL Developers, says its "shoe boxes" sell much faster than larger homes.
They are more popular, in the sense that these homes are built much faster than larger ones.
For this reason, it's much more profitable for our treasury.
However, he admits that the new standards give clearer instructions to developers, who were previously sidebreaking if they wished to offer too many small housing units in a project.
Too much stress
Singapore is a city-state.
If these new regulations could be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, by talking to Singaporeans working in the centre's financial district, it would seem that they would not have much effect.
'People are very stressed, houses are expensive, just like education, that's why people put it off to a later,' says a young executive.
Other persons may have children.
"But for me it's important to be able to have my money and my time," said another young man in his twenties.
Men and women mention their careers, stress and the cost of home ownership and education as well as reasons preventing them from having children.
Thus, although the government tries to convince its citizens to have children, when it comes to making babies, it is the Singaporeans themselves who have the last word.
