The Unasur Summit ended without the publication of the Lima Declaration
The Sixth Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) ended today in Peru without the declaration of the Lima Declaration, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the seven trustees present.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the Sixth Ordinary Meeting of Unasur Heads of State and Government, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially reported that it would be disclosed after the conclusion of the summit, and then claimed that it would be published from one time to the other on the Peruvian Government's website.
When asked about the text, they reported that its content had been explained by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, in brief statements to the press.
Journalists' access to information about the summit has been constantly restricted.
During the day, only the video without the sound of the presidential assembly with the message "private, restricted audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The lack of information circulating among journalists was that given by the press officers of some of the Unasur Governments that were present at the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesman.
The only document leaked during the day was a list of presidents present, which caused some unease among the hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who were asking for more information.
Later, the Peruvian Presidency sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but this was the speech by President Humala and not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the 3rd Summit in South America-Arab Countries (ASPA) and, on that occasion, although this was widely requested by the press, it had also not issued the so-called Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the official website of the ASPA, it is possible to verify that the document was published last March.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to establish safe transmission systems for all journalists, but they limited the availability of information as much as possible.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement between Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Hague Court that rules a different border between the two countries.
The Presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastian Piaera, met at the regional meeting and said that they would respect the ICJ's decision to hear the pleas of both parties in Lima's lawsuit against Santiago, which begins on Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the differences we are holding today before this international court", said President Humala, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has always been, and will continue to be, a country that respects international law, peaceful resolution of controversies, treaties and international tribunals," added President Piaera, giving President Humala a handshake, alongside the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ took place after Colombia denounced this week the Pact of Bogota by which it agreed to submit to the decisions of that international tribunal, after a decision on maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered to be seriously wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff of Venezuela, Hugo Chavez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011, after the dismissal of its former President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the appointment.
The host Chairman, Ollanta Humala, was instructed to open the proceedings in the morning and to close the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The trustee read the outcome document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that the lines of action of 31 projects had been set between the South American countries for a total investment of 17 million dollars.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that the Unasur countries would put in place "important approaches to achieving the goal of South American citizenship through the development of agreements on residence permits".
He informed that action would be taken to improve "cooperation in the fight against urban insecurity and international organised crime, actions to make medicines more accessible, access to the Internet at low cost throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters".
With a Europe in crisis, "economic consolidation (of Latin America) must not have a triumphalist matrix but must help to increase our productive matrix and to see a better future for our people", concluded President Humala.
"We decided to focus on a group of 31 iconic projects that improve the connection of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas... by uniting our countries and generating new economic channels," the Peruvian President said in a speech.
Among those projects, he mentioned that five concerned Peru and were on the cross-sections of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two were aimed at a more important connection with Ecuador, although it did not provide further details.
Similarly, the outcome document refers to the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will allow it to be reintegrated into the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and having good relations with its neighbours, is another theme discussed at the summit.
In this sense, the Colombian President, Juan Manuel Santos, said, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, the following Saturday in Mexico City to discuss the maritime dispute calmly through an ICJ ruling requested by Bogota.
"It is possible that tomorrow (Saturday) I have a meeting with President Daniel Ortega," said President Santos.
"We are going to revise all these paths, they are not exhaustive, including the Treaty with Nicaragua which will ask for a discussion with this country", he stressed.
"I hope to be able to tell President Ortega that we are going to sort this out in the most civilised and respectful way possible," added President Santos.
Presidents Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico City where they plan to witness the seizure of power by the country's new president, Enrique Peia Nieto.
Similarly, within the framework of the summit, the bloc's defence ministers will meet beforehand to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which attempts to strengthen dialogue and consensus in defence in the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are part of Unasur, although the latter country is suspended.
Peru holds the pro-tempore presidency of the regional bloc.
