Moreover, the President of Ecuador considers as "completely relevant" the desire of his Colombian counterpart, Juan Manuel Santos, to negotiate with Nicaragua the maritime boundaries between the two countries through the judgement of the International Court in The Hague, which will strengthen Nicaragua's maritime sovereignty.
At the moment, this judgement is not respected.
This is a problem between a South American country and a Central American country.
Conflicts are inevitable, but they must be overcome by the will to move forward together.
They must be resolved as a whole in order to overcome them and move forward.
At the same time, he expressed his confidence in the successful resolution of the dispute concerning the maritime borders between Peru and Chile in the same tribunal and stated that it was "beneficial that Latin America should seize international bodies if both countries agree to a judgement so firm as it is".
Referring to the possibility of his presentation as a candidate for the future presidential elections in Ecuador, with a view to running for a third consecutive term, he pointed out that he saw this possibility "with great optimism and joy, although it is sometimes quite difficult".
Correa assured that, if he lost the primaries in February 2013, he would withdraw from public life.
At the personal level, I have never been interested in power, but in situations as unfair as those of Ecuador, this socio-economic poverty can be resolved only through political power.
