AIDS-related deaths are now due to late detection.
Fabrizio was 21 years old when he was confirmed the test result: HIV-positive.
'It's as if the sky had fallen on my head,' he said, referring to the time of the announcement, that the doctor had tried to make 'less painful', in vain.
The young man hid him from his family.
He decided to take care of his illness alone and began to find out about him and his zeal was such that he had just celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients in the HIV unit of the Guadalajara Civil Hospital (HCG), in which he found himself in 1994 after many battles.
Fabrizio has been living with human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, something hard to imagine in the early 1990s, where there were many doubts, few treatment choices and more stigmas.
So even the director of an IMSS clinic avoided saying goodbye "because he was speechless."
At that time, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Today, it is possible to survive this syndrome and to have a good quality of life.
However, unaware of their disease, many people still arrive when the virus has already caused damage, "exhausted" their immune system and are victims of opportunistic infections.
31 years after the onset of AIDS in the world, in any case after the first reported cases, "the great victory today is that the survival of a patient who has started treatment at the right time and the survival of the general population is exactly the same", said the head of the HCG HIV unit, Jaime Andrade Villanueva, and he takes it as a reference that this information was validated in April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
The HIV/AIDS infectiologist and expert, Andrade Villanueva, commented that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is no longer a fatal disease, but that the number of years of survival and quality of life depends on the level of assignment of the immune system that patients have at the time of diagnosis, with better prospects for those not consuming drugs: up to 30 years for a CD4 cell count of up to 50 years.
Simply put, this means that for someone who gets a positive HIV diagnosis at 25, "as long as he remains under control, can live without problems until the age of 75," explained the scientist interviewed.
In order to place this progress in context, it is important to know that the life expectancy of Mexicans is now 76 years on average.
While mortality has decreased significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people who died as a result of AIDS increased from 6.678 cases in 2007 to 4.862 in 2011 (according to the UNAIDS annual report), it is also true that, since the onset of AIDS, 60 per cent of patients on the basis of national data have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and there were 187 deaths until May this year; however, we are assured that access to antiretroviral drugs has been universal since 2005.
So why are there still deaths?
I do not think the problem is concerned about access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's what happened in our hospital.
Over at least the last 12 years, we have never run out of medication, the problem is that patients are reaching very advanced stages because they do not know that they are infected, or they learn it at advanced stages of the disease.
It gives us an indisputable fact: "nine in ten patients arrive when they already have an opportunistic infection, what it takes to have a greater impact on overall mortality, is to carry out earlier diagnoses and, to do so, we must propose massive screening tests, to all the people who request it".
The specialists and members of the State Council for AIDS Prevention in Jalisco (Coesida) agree on his proposal, as do the patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who had to test his screening in a private laboratory, simply because a friend had done so and, despite his young age, he was already carrying AIDS and suffering from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancerous tumor.
Everything changes when you learn that you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die and they don't want to know anything.
"If I'm going to die, it's better for me to have fun three times a week," they say, "is not my case.
The change was beneficial, I eat well, I exercise, I take my medication.
To this day, his parents only know that he suffers from cancer.
I have a normal life, like anyone else.
"I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but co-responsible, I pay attention to myself and the other person," says Fabrizio, who agreed to share his intimacy with MILENIO JALISCO to help, through his testimony, those who are afraid today, during the World AIDS Day march.
If they take the test, if they have taken risks, the sooner they will know if they are HIV-positive and the better, and if they already have the diagnosis, they must know that we can live like everyone else, being responsible.
His message sums up the slogan of the battle against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms on the counter
There are many gaps between health programmes and ordinary citizens, says Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has embraced the cause of HIV.
And the greatest is prevention.
In all the places dedicated to this, 'we have actually increased the distribution of condoms, before we were given one or two, now we are given packets of a hundred, that is all very well, but as a result, as yet today, some do not have access to condoms,' he says.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are adolescents.
The question: "What are you going to do with it?", raised with sarcasm and value judgements by social workers, guidance counsellors, pharmacists and health professionals, is the question that teenagers don't want to hear, says the journalist.
He proposed to redirect that inefficient distribution; that condoms should not only be sold at counters, but should be found in public toilet dispensers and in places frequented by young people.
It is not a question of encouraging promiscuity.
It was also not a question of paying them the girls and the motel, as Governor Emilio Gonzalez replied when he had been asked whether there would be a distribution of condoms within his administration.
'It's not how sexuality works, the best thing is to provide condoms to people who are already sexually active,' he said.
Figures in Jalisco
There are 13.435 cumulative cases (12,158 AIDS and 1.317 HIV).
The State is the fourth largest country in the country in terms of the number of new and cumulative cases of AIDS and the 13th largest number of HIV-infected patients.
92% of the infections are carried out sexually, 6% by the blood route and 2% by the perinatal route.
It is estimated that 50,000 people are living with HIV, since for each case registered there are 4 or 5 people who do not know.
A judgment ratified on appeal by a United States court ignores the restructuring of the Vitro Group's debt through a commercial bankruptcy in Mexico. The scenario sets a bad precedent for all national companies with subsidiaries in the neighbouring country and with solvency problems.
It therefore appears that the procedures for the survival of companies authorized by Mexican law are not valid in the country with a star-tank banner, against international agreements.
From a practical point of view, the blow to the June 15, judgement of Judge Harlin Hale of the Bankruptcy Court for the North District of Texas, leaves Mexican companies defenceless in the face of the possibility of embargoing their properties beyond Bravo.
However, the resolution will allow the main glass manufacturer of Mexico to refer the Supreme Court of the United States on the basis of three inconsistencies.
First, while the judge of the case reports that creditors must register under the United States Bankruptcy Act, the New Orleans Fifth Circuit Court of Appeal asserts that the main proceeding is formalized commercial bankruptcy in Mexico.
The first point would imply denunciation of cooperation in cases of insolvency of companies with a transnational profile.
Indeed, the United Nations Model Law for the Uniformity of Commercial Law International had been created for that purpose by taking the American Law Institute as arbitrator.
Secondly, the judgment establishes that, without the inter-company vote, recognised in the critical estate of commercial bankruptcy, the debts incurred by subsidiaries of Vitro towards the parent company, the majority required for the approval of the restructuring could not have been obtained.
However, Mexican laws recognize this possibility.
In fact, the case of Vitro is not the first to use this plan.
There are half a dozen examples here, including Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, which the Federal Institute of Commercial Banks guaranteed the debts.
Moreover, what is certain is that, since the votes of the subsidiaries remained, in every way the creditors of Vitro who fought against it in the courts of the United States, i.e. the "vorur" funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited, would not have obtained the majority.
The vote was 45 to 37.
A data omitted by the appellate court.
On the other hand, Vitro has been blamed for the difficult situation it has faced since 2008 without stopping at the severe economic crisis facing the United States, passing on the costs to the country.
For the time being, the company of the Gonzalez Sada family will appeal to the same appellate court for the vote to take place in its entirety, i.e. with the five judges, since only three had voted.
The insurance claim will demand non-prosperity and requires the review of the case by a higher court, in this case the United States Supreme Court of Justice.
The most serious thing is that the court ignored a document sent by the Government of Mexico on behalf of the amicus curiae ("friend of the Court") detailing the procedure followed by Vitro under the Commercial Bankruptcy Act, pointing out that this freed it from the agreements signed by the two countries to bring it to the same level as paragraph 15 of the United States Bankruptcy Act.
In addition, he pointed out that the country had complied with the principles of the United Nations Commission on International Trade, i.e. the rules for cross-border insolvency cases, which guaranteed fairness for debtors and creditors.
Two-part carhy: they stun a Vitro and they stun the country.
