Hector "Hetin" Reyes "Basketball is my whole life"
The basketball globetrotrocharger "Hetin" Reyes spent more than 60 years of his life in relation to the field and, thanks to him, traveled around the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have a knowledge of the history of local basketball as big as that of Hector "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason for this is that before a cerebral hemorrhage doomed him to the wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in the sport for more than 60 years, whether as a lower league player, player of the national basketball team, manager and leader of the national team, the BSN, with the Bayamon Vaqueros or as president of the basketball federation.
"I wore several caps in basketball throughout my life, and even several at the same time, such as when I was president of the BSN, general manager of the national team and president of the federation during the 1990s," Reyes recalled during a visit by Primera Hora to his home in Bayamon, where he resided with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
"Basketball is my whole life."
Reyes does not exaggerate when he makes this statement.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and memories reminiscent of his extraordinary itinerary, testify to this.
Bayamon in the heart
Of all his memories, those he loves the most are those that remind him of his time as a player in the Vaqueros team in the mid-1950s until 1982, after spending 15 years as a co-manager or team manager.
"It was my best years, the years I took most advantage of because I had the chance to compete in eight championships of the Vaqueros from 1967, whether as manager, co-manager or leader.
It's been many years of satisfaction, including the five championships held from 1971 to 1975.
I then retired to the championship in 1981, the year Jerome Mincy joined the BSN team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great administrator, took over the team," says Reyes.
I remember Gene Bartow, who had been a leader here and was at the University of Alabama, Birmingham, said, "I have a tough player for you, he's two meters tall.
Do you want it?"
That's how Mincy, one of Puerto Rico's best players, started.
Bartow then recommended to me Raymond Gausse, who was naturalized and one of the best shooters.
I remember he said that if Mincy had allowed Bayamon to win a championship, Gausse would help us try to win another.
He rejoiced in the championship of the Vaqueros with Gausse, but only at a distance since in 1988 he was already the great manitou of the federation.
At that time, he preferred to take advantage of his and Mincy's responsibilities in the national team.
I remember when we first won it in the United States in the 1989 pre-Olympic tournament in Mexico City.
Then there was the 1990 World Cup, where we arrived 4th and where we should have won the bronze medal if that Canadian judge hadn't made us play the last game again, said Reyes.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you've seen?
She is among the best, as well as the one who defeated the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite is the Pan American Cuba Games in 1991, when we won gold and we beat the United States team, which was quite similar to the one that won bronze at the World Cup.
This team was not only composed of Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico Lopez and "Piculin" (Ortiz), there were also the young people (Javier) "Tozito" Colon and James Carter, the brothers Leon (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario "Quijote" Morales, who had not been able to attend the world of 90 due to a problem.
A team that was perhaps not the best in terms of individuals, but it gave us a gold medal and great joy at the pre-Olympic tournament in Neuquén, Argentina.
With players like "Canito" Nieves, Pablo Alicea and young Rolando Hourruitiner replacing players suspended by the Imbroglio of the Pan American Games in Mar del Plata, we won gold against all predictions.
Who was the best player in Puerto Rico?
Undoubtedly, this is Piculin Ortiz.
His statistics at the international tournament level are impressive.
No one in Puerto Rico dominated at this level, as Piculon did.
This is without taking into account his trajectory in the various leagues he played for.
Who was the best Puerto Rican leader?
It's very hard to say.
We had a good team of Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau, Armandito Torres.
In young people, I really like the work that Leo Arill does.
For you, what is your greatest success in the federation?
Having was one of the most glorious times on the national team between 1988 and 1995, and the fact that in the early 1990s the BSN had up to 17 teams in a season.
What do you have to do?
There are things I would have liked to put in place, such as the regionalisation of minor categories.
For example, that Ponce's boys play only in their area and only face teams from other corners of the island during national playoffs.
Today, young people travel and play too much when this is not necessarily necessary.
I have at least seen the advantage of compulsory certifications and courses for managers, field staff and arbitrators.
It makes me happy.
What are you doing today?
In general, I listen to music, I watch clips from my time on YouTube, I enjoy my grandchildren and, from time to time, I attend basketball games.
And of course, I take advantage of the company of my wife, Isabel, who has always been by my side.
Death of actor Larry Hagman
Larry Hagman, born on 21 September 1931 in Forth Worth, Texas, became known worldwide by the lead role of John Ross Ewing, better known as J.R., in the television series "Dallas", in which he embodied an unscrupulous, fearsome and manipulative businessman.
Larry Hagman, whose role as unscrupulous oil magnate J.R. Ewing in the television series "Dallas" became a symbol of avarice in the 1980s, died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who had returned this year as J.R. in a new season of "Dallas", died of cancer complications on Friday night, according to a family statement sent to The Associated Press for Warner Bros., production house of "Dallas".
"Larry was back in his dear hometown of Dallas, again playing the ironic role he loved most," said the family.
Larry's family and close friends were with him in Dallas on Thanksgiving holiday.
Linda Gray, who played his wife's role in the original series and later, was with Hagman when he died in a hospital in Dallas, said his press officer, Jeffrey Lane.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, loving and talented, and I'm going to miss him a lot.
"He was an exceptional person and he lived life to the fullest," Gray said in a statement.
Doctors had diagnosed Larry Hagman with liver cirrhosis in 1992 and had admitted to having drunk a lot for many years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignant liver tumor and had a transplant.
Several years before "Dallas", Hagman had become known on television as an ordinary guy in the NBC series "Jinny of My Dreams" from 1965 to 1970.
In this, he played the role of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life was transformed when he discovered an attractive genius, played by Barbara Eden, and brought her home.
He also starred in two short-lived comedies, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His film roles include critical roles in "The Band", "Harry and Tonto" and "Primary Colors".
But it was thanks to his masterful interpretation of the delightfully abhorrent J.R. that Larry Hagman had his greatest success.
The CBS drama series on the Ewing clan and their relatives aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan "Who killed J.R.?", invented to maintain the suspense around an episode full of emotions in which the Hagman character is almost murdered, generated speculation around the world and millions of dollars played in betting.
Thanks to this, among other things, the series reached an audience record at that time.
When the response was revealed in an episode in November 1980, 41 million viewers averaged their screens and made "Dallas" the second most watched entertainment program in the world, after the final episode of "MASH" in 1983, which had gathered 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-in-in-sister (played by Mary Crosby) who shot him.
J.R. had put her to pregnant and subsequently threatened to accuse her of prostitution if she did not leave the city, but other people also had reasons to assault her.
Hagman played the role of Ewing as a corrupt and insatiable man but with a charismatic smile: a dishonest entrepreneur and an unfaithful husband who tried to internalize his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray).
"I know what it would take as an epitaph for J.R," said Hagman in 1988.
We should write: "The honest citizen J.R. "Ewing".
This is the only part he lost.
Victoria Principal, co-protagonist of the original series, recalled on Friday from Hangman as a "big man, both on the small screen and in life".
It's unforgettable, and irreplaceable, for millions of fans around the world, and in the hearts of all of us, who have been lucky enough to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new edition of "Dallas" were broadcast a few months ago with great success on the TNT channel.
The recording of five episodes is already over for the second season and a sixth is in the process of being made, the channel informed.
So far, neither Warner nor the TNT has communicated how Hangman's death will be integrated into the series.
Originally from Fort Worth, Texas, he was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who enjoyed celebrity with classic works such as "South Pacific" and "Peter Pan".
