A course on "End of the World" has just begun
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
This semester, when religious teacher Stuart Charmé decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew that he was launching an irresistible hook there: the end of the "big count" of the Maya calendar on 21 December, to which many people refer as proof of the end of the impending world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea what was waiting for him in the following months: the catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, a fiscal abyss that some dubbed the "Armageddon of debt" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where late-time Christian theorists thought that the apocalypse would be triggered.
"I didn't realize it was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever seen," Professor Charmé told his students at Rutgers-Camden University, New Jersey, this week.
If we look at what happened in the world today as if we were 30 days later and we were telling it, it was a very good time.
And we have to remember that what is bad is good for those who believe in apocalypse.
And he's not the only teacher giving classes on the "end of the world" this semester, which will, in theory, be the last in history.
At Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker teaches the course "Media, Culture and End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs, and global warming.
'We analyse this because these ideas proliferate over time,' he said, and the way they offer hypothetical scenarios guides a certain human course.
If nuclear weapons fell into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyse films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with real-life examples.
'I tried to inform my students about what was possible, likely, credible and impossible,' said Vacker.
On the main campus of Pennsylvania State University, Latin American History Professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of Art History and Anthropology, teamed up to give a lecture, simply entitled "The End of the World".
'We're adding '2012' to have the opportunity to give the course again, in case the world does not disappear,' said Professor Restall.
Despite the "imminent disaster", students must study, create projects and take their final exams.
In the state of Pennsylvania, the final exam will be held the day before the Apocalypse, leaving students no choice but to work "until the very night of the supposed end of the world," Restall said.
The courses proved to be quite popular.
'It was complete in two hours,' said Restall about his course for top students, consisting of 35 students.
We received e-mail messages several weeks before the start of the semester, from people who asked if there was still room.
Students, for their part, assure that the course is one of the most interesting.
"It fascinated me to see what people are able to do to comfort themselves," says Bridgid Robinson, a 23-year-old student of religion and sociology from Haddonfield, New Jersey, University of Rutgers-Camden.
For the fear of the Apocalypse, whether secular or religious, is only a matter of comfort, or lack of comfort.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old student in psychology and infirmary, claims to have watched all the apocalyptic films.
'I had never heard of a course that taught this subject,' he said.
I like it.
But none of the students interviewed, let alone a professor, told us that we believe in the end of the world on December 21.
"Our first project dealt with Mayan prophecy, and somehow we discredited it," says Julie Egle, a senior-year student at Temple, a 21-year-old student from West Chester.
The Maya never predicted the end of the world, it's just a key date on the calendar, Restall said.
But I concede that there is anxiety about the apocalypse in Western culture, going back several centuries, which causes people to react to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet has caused this speculation to flourish.
'In other parts of the world, people don't think about that,' he says.
The majority of these are the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who is teaching in the Philippines this year, responded quickly when asked if he knew that we were giving classes here about the "end of the world".
"The Philippines is not participating in the end of the world," he replied, as if it were an exception from a higher authority.
We have a grace from the Pope.
Restall points out that over the years, we've talked about the many supposed dates of the last judgment, and he says that if nothing happens on December 21, "people will immediately start thinking about the next date" or philosophizing the fact that December 21 marks the beginning of a seven-year period at the end of which the world will disappear.
Students and teachers take the date lightly.
Several have told us that they are thinking of going to 'end of the world's holidays.
"Sometimes I call friends and we laugh at them together," commented Samira Ford, a 20-year-old communications student.
